8 SECTION 5. IC 16-21-9-4 IS AMENDED TO READ AS
9 FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) A nonprofit
10 hospital shall develop:
11 (1) an organizational mission statement that identifies the
12 hospital's commitment to serving the health care needs of the
13 community; and
14 (2) a community benefits plan defined as an operational plan for
15 serving the community's health care needs that:
16 (A) sets out goals and objectives for providing community
17 benefits that include charity care and government sponsored
18 indigent health care; and
19 (B) identifies the populations and communities served by the
20 hospital; and
21 (C) includes a preceptor as set forth in subsection (b).
22 A nonprofit hospital shall spend more on the nonprofit hospital's
23 community benefits plan than on the nonprofit hospital's estimated
24 value of tax exemptions, as calculated under section 7(a)(8) of this
25 chapter.
26 (b) A nonprofit hospital shall maintain at least one (1) preceptor
27 in at least sixty percent (60%) of the nonprofit hospital's clinical
28 departments during each reporting year as part of the nonprofit
29 hospital's community benefits plan requirement. A nonprofit
30 hospital may satisfy this requirement through a combination of any
31 of the following:
32 (1) Employed clinicians.
33 (2) Contracted clinicians.
34 (3) Shared preceptors participating in regional training
35 partnerships.
36 (c) A nonprofit hospital may count preceptor activities as
37 community benefits expenditures for reporting purposes under this
38 chapter. Qualifying expenditures for the operation of a preceptor
39 include the following:
40 (1) Salaries.
41 (2) Stipends.
42 (3) Administrative support.
